column7: {'text'": '"Import tree dataset from a Comma Separated Value (CSV) file. datatree should be the node to import the data into. There are 3 possible formats to import. If format is 1
column8: then the data is imported as a table
column9: meaning each sub-node of datatree is a row in the table
column10: and each sub-node of each row is a cell in the table. This is the same as using the importtable() command. If format is 2
column11: then the data is imported as a simple data series. The csv file is assumed to have one column
column12: and each row''s value is imported into a sub-node of datatree. If format is 3
column13: then the data is imported as a series of x
column14: y pairs. The csv file is assumed to have 2 columns. Row 1 column 1 of the csv file is imported as sub-node 1 of datatree
column15: row 1 column 2 is imported as sub-node 2 of datatree
column16: row 2 column 1 is imported as sub-node 3 of datatree
column17: and so forth. Commands for creating
column19: and accessing statistical data; including probability distributions.'"}"

column5: {'text'": '"Makes number streams antithetic. Using this command
column6: users can switch random streams to generate numbers between 1 and 0; rather than the default of 0 to 1. This is helpful for determining if random numbers are having a big affect on the results of the model. It''s also useful when experimenting with massive models and there isn''t sufficient time to run the model for multiple iterations as required for good statistical sampling. The user can then choose to do just one regular run and one antithetic run of the model to obtain two diametrically apposed results. These two results can be averaged for an approximation that is somewhat better than if each run of the model used random stream generators without antithetic sampling. Commands for creating

column37: '"text'": '"STAT_CONF_INTERVAL_HALF_WIDTH - calculates the confidence interval half-width of the set.\n\t\t\tPass in p1 to define the desired\n\t\t\tconfidence percentage. FlexSim will return precise values for percentages at 80%
column42: and 99.8% and for\n\t\t\tsample sizes at or below 100 degrees of freedom. For percentages not in this set

column44: it will return an 80% confidence interval. Since an \n\t\t\t80% confidence interval will be a \'"wider\'" interval
column45: we clamp up to be \'"safer\'" with the wider interval. Confidence\n\t\t\tintervals above 99.8 will simply return 0 (i.e. not valid). For degrees \n\t\t\tof freedom above above 100

column11: reset or add data to a histogram

column16: define the appropriate data for the operation. The first parameter should be the main node in the tree that holds the graph/histo data. The second parameter should be either 1
column19: and defines the type of data that the node holds. 1 means graphx data. For this data type the node contains a list of sub-nodes
column20: and each sub-node contains a number that is a unique point in a data series. 2 means graphxy. For this data type
column21: the node again contains a list of sub-nodes but this time the sub-nodes are paired together as x/y pairs. Nodes ranked 1 and 2 hold the x and y values for one data point
column22: nodes 3 and 4 hold x and y values for the next data point
column23: etc. A type parameter of 3 means histo data. Here the node holds data associated with a histogram.  The action parameter should be either 1
column26: and defines the action that you want to do. 1 means a create operation. This is only needed for histogram type data
column27: as it needs to set up the node''s sub-tree structure. To create a histogram plot
column28: pass the minimum value for the histogram as the x parameter
column29: the maximum value of the histogram as the y value
column32: as the z parameter. An action parameter value of 2 means you want to reset the data. This will clear the content of the node for graphx or graphxy data
column33: and will reset the histogram values for histogram data. An action parameter value of 3 means you want to add a data point. For graphx and histo data
column34: pass the data point as the x parameter. For graphxy data
column35: pass the as the x and y paramters. In summary: Type: 1-graphx/2-graphxy/3-histo. Commands for creating

If the item cannot be pulled for any of various reasons (such as closed ports or the item not being released)
column9: then this command returns 0. The bypassflags parameter is a bitwise combination of macros that start with BYPASS_ to specify certain criteria to ignore in determining item availability. Commands associated with FixedResource objects. Most of these commands are used when developing custom behavior for the BasicConveyor or BasicFR object.'"}"

column8: {'text'": '"Tells the fixedresource to evaluate its pull requirement for the passed item that is in the object through the input port portnr. If the pull evaluation is true
column9: this command pulls the item immediately. This command returns 1 if the item was successfully pulled and 0 if not. If the item cannot be pulled for any of various reasons (such as closed ports or the item not being released)
column10: then this command returns 0. The bypassflags parameter is a bitwise combination of macros that start with BYPASS_ to specify certain criteria to ignore in determining item availability. You can specify BYPASS_ALL to immediately pull the item regardless of availability. Commands associated with FixedResource objects. Most of these commands are used when developing custom behavior for the BasicConveyor or BasicFR object.'"}"

column8: {'text'": '"Receives a message from the specified connection. This command operates differently in flexscript vs. c++. In c++
column9: buffer must be a valid pointer to a char* destination into which the read bytes will be copied. The return value will be the total number of bytes received. Up to bufsize bytes from the clients message will be read and stored in the preallocated character array called buf. In flexscript
column11: buffer should be passed as NULL
column12: and the return value will be the actual string that is received. If noblocking = 1
column13: then this command does not block FlexSim program execution
column15: FlexSim program execution will block (freeze) until something is received from the client. Commands for communicating with external applications such as sockets

column5: {'text'": '"Sets the shape frame of an object'"}"
column6: {'text'": '"Sets the frame attribute of the object to the framenumber.  The frame defines which 3D image to display. \n\t\tThis is a nice way of changing the 3D shape of an object on the fly. There are two ways to define frames on an object.\n\t\tFirst
column7: you can do it through the naming of various 3D files. For example
column8: if the object was assigned Operator.3ds as \n\t\tits default shape
column9: and there are additional files in the same directory as \n\t\tOperator.3ds named OperatorFRAME1.3ds
column11: then the frame attribute could be \n\t\tset to 0
column14: or 3 which would change the displayed shape to each of the 3ds files respectively. Secondly
column15: you can \n\t\tadd sub-nodes to an obejct''s shape attribute
column16: each with a path to the 3D file associated with that frame. Subsequently
column17: \n\t\tframe 1 would be associated with the shape attribute''s first sub-node
column18: etc. This is the method used within FlexSim''s \n\t\tenvironment to define shape frames. If toframe is a string
column19: then the latter method is assumed
column20: and it will find the \n\t\tshape attribute sub-node with the corresponding name. One use of this command \n\t\twould be to change the 3d shape in the OnDown trigger to show a \'"broken\'" shape. Commands for accessing and assigning data on objects.'"}"

column8: {'text'": '"Sets the value of an animation variable on an object. Animation variables are attributes of an animation \n\tthat may need to dynamically change for different runs of the animation
column9: such as surrogates
column11: \n\tor position/rotation/size values of a given keyframe. For example
column12: you may use surrogates in building your animation.\n\tYou do this by choosing a default visual from the flowitem bin to use as you create the animation. Then when the \n\tsimulation runs
column13:
you substitute real flowitems in for those surrogates when you run the simulation. You do this 
	substitution by setting the value of an animation variable that you''ve associated with that surrogate to the actual
	reference to the flowitem. Another example is you may use an animation variable to dynamically define the z position

column7:
{'text'": '"Sets the normal vector for shading subsequent vertices in OpenGL drawing. 
	Polygons will be flat shaded unless normals are applied to them. 
	A normal is a vector that is perpendicular to the polygon and points in the direction the 
	polygon is facing. Remember polygons with vertices defined in a counter-clockwise winding 
	points forward per the '"right-hand rule'". Polygon shading is based on the angle between 
	the normals and the light source. Normals are applied to each vertex in the same way 
	colors are
column8: but is usually just defined at the start of each polygon definition. When a \n\tpolygon''s normals point directly at the light source
column9: they are brightly shaded; and are \n\tdarker shaded when the angles are skewed. You can refer to standard OpenGL documentation \n\tfor more information if needed. Commands associated with drawing graphics in the planar
column11: or perspective views. Draw commands are designed for use in OnDraw events such as the \'"Custom Draw Code\'" field found in an object''s Properties window.'"}"
